.SH NAME
Bitcoin::Crypto::Script::Runner \- Bitcoin Script runner
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 2
\&        use Bitcoin::Crypto::Script::Runner;
\&        use Data::Dumper;
\&
\&        my $runner = Bitcoin::Crypto::Script::Runner\->new;
\&
\&        # provide an instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Script
\&        # runs the script all at once
\&        $runner\->execute($script);
\&
\&        # ... or: runs the script step by step
\&        $runner\->start($script);
\&        while ($runner\->step) {
\&                print \*(Aqrunner step, stack: \*(Aq;
\&                print Dumper($runner\->stack);
\&        }
\&
\&        print \*(AqFAILURE\*(Aq unless $runner\->success;
\&        print \*(Aqresulting stack: \*(Aq;
\&        print Dumper($runner\->stack);
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This class instances can be used to execute Bitcoin scripts defined as
instances of Bitcoin::Crypto::Script. Scripts can be executed in one go or
step by step, and the execution stack is available through an accessor.
.PP
One runner can be used to execute scripts multiple times. Each time you call
\&\f(CW\*(C`execute\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`start\*(C'\fR, the runner state is reset. Initial stack state can be
provided to either one of those methods. This provides better control over
execution than "run" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Script, which simply executes the script
and returns its stack.
.SH INTERFACE
.IX Header "INTERFACE"
.SS Attributes
.IX Subsection "Attributes"
\fItransaction\fR
.IX Subsection "transaction"
.PP
Instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction wrapped inside
\&\f(CW\*(C`Bitcoin::Crypto::Script::Transaction\*(C'\fR for some extra data. It is optional,
but some opcodes will refuse to function without it.
.PP
\&\fIpredicate:\fR \f(CW\*(C`has_transaction\*(C'\fR
.PP
\&\fIwriter:\fR \f(CW\*(C`set_transaction\*(C'\fR
.PP
\fIflags\fR
.IX Subsection "flags"
.PP
An instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Flags. If not passed, full set
of consensus flags will be assumed (same as calling
"new" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Flags with no arguments).
.PP
\&\fIwriter:\fR \f(CW\*(C`set_flags\*(C'\fR
.PP
\fIscript\fR
.IX Subsection "script"
.PP
The current script being executed. Will be set automatically in "start".
\&\f(CW\*(C`set_script\*(C'\fR can be used to set it manually.
.PP
\&\fBNot assignable in the constructor\fR
.PP
\fIstack\fR
.IX Subsection "stack"
.PP
\&\fBNot assignable in the constructor\fR
.PP
Array reference \- the stack which is used during script execution. Last item in
this array is the stack top. Use \f(CW\*(C`$runner\->stack\->[\-1]\*(C'\fR to examine the stack top.
.PP
Each item on the stack is a byte string. Use "to_int" and "to_bool" to
transform it into an integer or boolean value in the same fashion bitcoin
script interpreter does it.
.PP
\fIalt_stack\fR
.IX Subsection "alt_stack"
.PP
\&\fBNot assignable in the constructor\fR
.PP
Array reference \- alt stack, used by \f(CW\*(C`OP_TOALTSTACK\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`OP_FROMALTSTACK\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\fIoperations\fR
.IX Subsection "operations"
.PP
\&\fBNot assignable in the constructor\fR
.PP
A proxy to "operations" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Script of the selected "script".
.PP
\fIpos\fR
.IX Subsection "pos"
.PP
\&\fBNot assignable in the constructor\fR
.PP
Positive integer \- the position of the operation to be run in the next step
(from "operations").
.PP
\fIcodeseparator\fR
.IX Subsection "codeseparator"
.PP
\&\fBNot assignable in the constructor\fR
.PP
Positive integer \- "pos" of the last encountered codeseparator, or undef
if none was encountered.
.SS Methods
.IX Subsection "Methods"
\fInew\fR
.IX Subsection "new"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $object = $class\->new(%data)
.Ve
.PP
This is a standard Moo constructor, which can be used to create the object. It
takes arguments specified in "Attributes".
.PP
Returns class instance.
.PP
\fIexecute\fR
.IX Subsection "execute"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $object = $object\->execute($script, \e@initial_stack = [])
.Ve
.PP
Executes the script in one go. Returns runner instance (for chaining).
.PP
\&\f(CW$script\fR must be an instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Script. If you only have
a serialized script in a string, call
"from_serialized" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Script first to get a proper script
instance. \f(CW$initial_stack\fR will be used to pre\-populate the stack before
running the script.
.PP
After the method returns call "stack" to get execution stack. This can be
done in a single line:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        my $stack = $runner\->execute($script)\->stack;
.Ve
.PP
If errors occur, an exception will be thrown.
.PP
\fIstart\fR
.IX Subsection "start"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $object = $object\->start($script, \e@initial_stack = [])
.Ve
.PP
Same as "execute", but only sets initial runner state and does not actually
execute any script opcodes. "step" must be called to continue the execution.
.PP
\fIstep\fR
.IX Subsection "step"
.PP
.Vb 3
\&        while ($runner\->step) {
\&                # do something after each step
\&        }
.Ve
.PP
Executes the next script opcode. Returns a false value if the script finished
the execution, and a true value otherwise.
.PP
"start" must be called before this method is called.
.PP
Note that not every opcode will take a step to execute. This means that this script:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        OP_1 OP_IF OP_PUSHDATA1 1 0x1f OP_ENDIF
.Ve
.PP
will take four steps to execute (\f(CW\*(C`OP_1\*(C'\fR \-> \f(CW\*(C`OP_IF\*(C'\fR \-> \f(CW0x1f\fR \-> \f(CW\*(C`OP_ENDIF\*(C'\fR).
.PP
This one however:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        OP_1 OP_IF OP_PUSHDATA1 1 0x1f OP_ELSE OP_PUSHDATA1 2 0xe15e OP_ENDIF
.Ve
.PP
will also take four steps (\f(CW\*(C`OP_1\*(C'\fR \-> \f(CW\*(C`OP_IF\*(C'\fR \-> \f(CW0x1f\fR \-> \f(CW\*(C`OP_ELSE\*(C'\fR).
This happens because \f(CW\*(C`OP_ELSE\*(C'\fR performs a jump past \f(CW\*(C`OP_ENDIF\*(C'\fR.
If the initial op was \f(CW\*(C`OP_0\*(C'\fR, the execution would be \f(CW\*(C`OP_0\*(C'\fR \-> \f(CW\*(C`OP_IF\*(C'\fR \->
\&\f(CW0xe15e\fR \-> \f(CW\*(C`OP_ENDIF\*(C'\fR. No \f(CW\*(C`OP_ELSE\*(C'\fR since it was jumped over and reaching
\&\f(CW\*(C`OP_ENDIF\*(C'\fR.
.PP
These details should not matter usually, but may be confusing if you would
want to for example print your stack step by step. When in doubt, check \f(CW\*(C`$runner\->pos\*(C'\fR, which contains the position of the \fBnext\fR opcode to execute.
.PP
\fIsubscript\fR
.IX Subsection "subscript"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $subscript = $object\->subscript()
.Ve
.PP
Returns current subscript \- part of the running script from after the last
codeseparator, also known as scriptCode.
.PP
Depending on the input spending segwit, the subscript will behave differently:
.IP \(bu 4
pre\-segwit
.Sp
Removes all codeseparators after the last executed codeseparator. \fBCurrently
does not remove the signature (known as FindAndDelete)\fR.
.IP \(bu 4
segwit
.Sp
Only removes the part up to the last executed \f(CW\*(C`OP_CODESEPARATOR\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\fIsuccess\fR
.IX Subsection "success"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $boolean = $object\->success()
.Ve
.PP
Returns a boolean indicating whether the script execution was successful.
.PP
\fIis_tapscript\fR
.IX Subsection "is_tapscript"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $boolean = $object\->is_tapscript()
.Ve
.PP
Returns true if currently executed script is a tapscript.
.SS "Helper methods"
.IX Subsection "Helper methods"
\fIto_int\fR
.IX Subsection "to_int"
.PP
\fIfrom_int\fR
.IX Subsection "from_int"
.PP
.Vb 2
\&        my $int = $runner\->to_int($byte_vector, $max_bytes = 4);
\&        my $byte_vector = $runner\->from_int($int);
.Ve
.PP
These methods encode and decode numbers in format which is used on "stack".
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`to_int\*(C'\fR limits the size of an integer to \f(CW$max_bytes\fR.
.PP
On 32\-bit machines, BigInts are used. \f(CW\*(C`to_int\*(C'\fR will return an instance of
Math::BigInt, while \f(CW\*(C`from_int\*(C'\fR can accept it (but it should also handle
regular numbers just fine). On 64\-bit machines, perl numbers will be used.
.PP
Most of the time, the internal representation of integers on the stack should
not matter. If it does matter though, \f(CW\*(C`BITCOIN_CRYPTO_USE_BIGINTS\*(C'\fR
environmental variable can be set to \f(CW1\fR to force use of BigInts on 64 bit
machines.
.PP
\fIto_bool\fR
.IX Subsection "to_bool"
.PP
\fIto_minimal_bool\fR
.IX Subsection "to_minimal_bool"
.PP
\fIfrom_bool\fR
.IX Subsection "from_bool"
.PP
These methods encode and decode booleans in format which is used on "stack".
\&\f(CW\*(C`to_minimal_bool\*(C'\fR variant is used to enforce "minimal_if" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Flags.
.PP
\fIstack_serialized\fR
.IX Subsection "stack_serialized"
.PP
Returns the serialized stack. Any null vectors will be transformed to \f(CW0x00\fR.
